# T2K: Japan's Long-Baseline Neutrino Endeavor

One might think that probing the universe's most elusive particles would be a straightforward affair, but then you'd be mistaken. The [T2K](/T2K) experiment, a rather ambitious undertaking, stands as a testament to humanity's persistent, and frankly, somewhat obsessive, quest to understand the ephemeral nature of [neutrinos](/Neutrino). Its name, a rather uninspired acronym, simply denotes the journey: "[Tokai](/T%C5%8Dkai,_Ibaraki) to [Kamioka](/Kamioka,_Gifu)." This isn't just a commute; it's a 295-kilometer (183 mi) odyssey for subatomic particles, designed to unravel some of the universe's most fundamental secrets.

At its core, [T2K](/T2K) is a [particle physics](/Particle_physics) experiment, meticulously studying the perplexing phenomenon known as [neutrino oscillations](/Neutrino_oscillations). These are not your everyday oscillations; we're talking about the quantum mechanical shapeshifting of [accelerator neutrinos](/Accelerator_neutrinos) as they traverse vast distances. The sheer scale of this endeavor requires an international cooperation of approximately 500 physicists and engineers, representing over 60 research institutions from Europe, Asia, and North America. It's a significant enough undertaking to be formally recognized as a [CERN](/CERN) experiment (RE13), lending it an air of legitimacy that even I can't entirely dismiss.

The first phase of [T2K](/T2K) operation, which some might call the 'warm-up act,' collected data diligently from 2010 until 2021. Now, with the universe still stubbornly refusing to yield all its secrets, the second phase, imaginatively dubbed [T2K-II](/T2K), is slated to commence in 2023. This will continue its relentless data accumulation until 2027, when it will presumably hand over the baton to its successor, the [Hyper-Kamiokande](/Hyper-Kamiokande) experiment. Because, clearly, there's no rest for the particle-obsessed.

[T2K](/T2K) holds the distinction of being the first experiment to unequivocally observe the *appearance* of [electron neutrinos](/Electron_neutrino) within a [muon neutrino](/Muon_neutrino) [beam](/Particle_beam). A feat that, for those who appreciate such things, was a rather significant confirmation of what theorists had been muttering about. Beyond this initial splash, it has delivered what are considered the world's best measurements of the oscillation parameter θ₂₃, a value that, while seemingly arbitrary to the uninitiated, is crucial for understanding how these ghostly particles mix. Furthermore, it has provided a tantalizing hint—a mere whisper, really—of a substantial [matter-antimatter asymmetry](/CP_violation) in [neutrino oscillations](/Neutrino_oscillations). This particular nugget of data could, if proven robust, bring us a step closer to explaining the rather awkward fact that our [Universe](/Baryon_asymmetry) is so decidedly [matter-dominated](/Baryon_asymmetry), rather than a chaotic void of mutual annihilation. A small win for existence, one might say.

The operational pipeline for [T2K](/T2K) begins at the [J-PARC](/J-PARC) facility (Japan Proton Accelerator Research Complex) in [Tokai](/T%C5%8Dkai,_Ibaraki), nestled on Japan's east coast. Here, an intense [beam](/Particle_beam) of [muon neutrinos](/Muon_neutrino) is conjured into existence. This beam is then aimed with astonishing precision towards the [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) far detector, a colossal water tank situated 295 kilometers (183 mi) away in the city of [Hida](/Hida,_Gifu), within the [Gifu prefecture](/Gifu_prefecture). Before these neutrinos embark on their epic journey, their initial properties and composition are carefully measured by a system of near detectors, positioned a mere 280 meters (920 ft) from the beam production point at the [J-PARC](/J-PARC) site. Then, after their long, unhindered voyage through the Earth's crust, their properties are measured *again* in the [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) detector. By comparing the content of different [neutrino](/Neutrino) flavors at these two disparate locations, physicists can precisely quantify the [oscillation](/Neutrino_oscillation) probability that occurred during the neutrinos' subterranean transit. The [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) detector is particularly adept at detecting interactions from both [muon](/Muon) and [electron neutrinos](/Electron_neutrino), allowing it to register both the expected *disappearance* of [muon neutrinos](/Muon_neutrino) and the more intriguing *appearance* of their [electron](/Electron) counterparts in the beam. It’s all very elegant, if you enjoy watching particles do a cosmic disappearing act.

## Physics program

The [T2K](/T2K) experiment, in its nascent stages, was proposed in 2003 with a set of rather ambitious, if predictable, measurement goals. These were, of course, presented as crucial steps forward in our understanding of the universe, and who am I to argue?

Specifically, the initial objectives included:

*   The groundbreaking discovery of νᵤ → νₑ [oscillations](/Neutrino_oscillation), which would finally, definitively confirm that the elusive last unknown mixing angle, θ₁₃, was not, in fact, zero. A minor detail, perhaps, but one that kept many physicists up at night.
*   The precise measurement of the oscillation parameters Δm²₂₃ and θ₂₃, achieved through diligent studies of [muon neutrino](/Muon_neutrino) disappearance. Because if neutrinos are going to vanish, we might as well know *how* they're doing it.
*   A dedicated search for [sterile neutrino](/Sterile_neutrino) oscillations, which, if they existed, would manifest as an inexplicable deficit of [neutral current](/Neutral_current) [neutrino](/Neutrino) interactions. A cosmic game of hide-and-seek, with potentially profound implications.
*   Measurements of various interaction [cross-sections](/Cross_section_(physics)) for different types of [neutrinos](/Neutrino) and target materials within an energy range of a few [GeV](/Gigaelectronvolt). Because understanding how these particles interact is, apparently, terribly important for building better models.

Since its inauguration and the commencement of data collection in 2010, the [T2K](/T2K) experiment has, to its credit, delivered a rather impressive list of world-class results. It's almost as if they knew what they were doing:

*   The definitive confirmation of [electron neutrino](/Electron_neutrino) appearance within the [muon neutrino](/Muon_neutrino) beam (νᵤ → νₑ). This was, for the record, the very first time that [neutrinos](/Neutrino) produced in one flavor were explicitly observed to have transformed into another. A genuinely impressive parlor trick for subatomic particles.
*   The most precise measurement to date of the θ₂₃ parameter. A detail, yes, but one that refines our cosmic map.
*   Establishment of stringent limits on [sterile neutrino](/Sterile_neutrino) oscillation parameters, derived from meticulous studies conducted in both the near ND280 and far [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) detectors. So far, the universe seems disappointingly free of these hypothetical particles, but the search continues.
*   A plethora of [cross-section](/Cross_section_(physics)) measurements for both [electron](/Electron) and [muon neutrinos](/Muon_neutrino) and antineutrinos. These include inclusive [charged current](/Charged_current) (CC) interactions, CC interactions without [pions](/Pion) in the final state, and those *with* a single [pion](/Pion), coherent [pion](/Pion) production, and [neutral current](/Neutral_current) interactions, among others. These measurements were performed on diverse targets such as [carbon](/Carbon), [water](/Water), and [iron](/Iron), because apparently, [neutrinos](/Neutrino) are quite particular about their interaction partners.
*   The first significant constraint on the δCP parameter, a value directly responsible for the [matter-antimatter asymmetry](/CP_violation) observed in [neutrino oscillations](/Neutrino_oscillations). This is where things get truly interesting, if you're into existential questions.

The δCP parameter, taking values from -π to π (or, for those who prefer degrees, from −180° to 180°), is quantified by comparing the [oscillations](/Neutrino_oscillation) of [neutrinos](/Neutrino) to those of their antimatter counterparts, antineutrinos. If [CP symmetry](/CP_violation) were perfectly conserved—meaning oscillation probabilities for [neutrinos](/Neutrino) and antineutrinos would be identical—then δCP would be precisely 0 or ±π. [T2K](/T2K) has provided the initial, and thus far the most robust, constraint on this parameter, effectively ruling out nearly half of its possible values at a 3σ (99.7%) significance level. More strikingly, it rejected both [CP](/CP_violation) conserving points at a 95% significance, strongly suggesting that [CP violation](/CP_violation) might be rather substantial within the neutrino sector.

This finding is not merely an academic curiosity. [CP violation](/CP_violation) is one of the crucial [conditions](/Baryogenesis) first proposed by the Russian physicist [Andrei Sakharov](/Andrei_Sakharov), deemed necessary to [produce](/Baryogenesis) the observed excess of matter over antimatter in the [early universe](/Big_Bang)—the very asymmetry that constitutes our [matter-built Universe](/Baryon_asymmetry) today. While [CP violation](/CP_violation) in the [quark](/Quark) sector was confirmed as early as 1964, its magnitude is far too minuscule to account for the cosmic imbalance we observe. A strong [CP violation](/CP_violation) within the neutrino sector, however, could potentially lead to matter excess through a process known as [leptogenesis](/Leptogenesis), making this measurement a profoundly important step in understanding the universe's origin story. It's a grand narrative, really, all hinging on tiny, elusive particles.

Of course, [T2K](/T2K) isn't the only game in town. The [NOvA](/NOvA) experiment, another [neutrino oscillation](/Neutrino_oscillation) endeavor, also seeks to measure δCP by comparing νᵤ → νₑ and νᵤ → νₑ oscillation channels. [NOvA](/NOvA) is conducted in the United States, observing [accelerator neutrino](/Accelerator_neutrino) oscillations over a distance of 810 km, from its beam production site at [Fermilab](/Fermilab) to its far detector in Ash River, [Minnesota](/Minnesota). While [NOvA](/NOvA) has contributed its own measurements of δCP, they are currently less precise and, rather inconveniently, show a slight tension with the [T2K](/T2K) results. The best-fit point from [T2K](/T2K) lies in a region disfavored by [NOvA](/NOvA) at a 90% confidence level. Such is the nature of cutting-edge physics; sometimes, the universe refuses to give a clear answer immediately. Efforts are currently underway to perform a joint fit combining data from both experiments, hopefully to quantify the consistency—or, more entertainingly, the inconsistency—between them.

Looking ahead, the planned upgrades to [T2K](/T2K) are expected to yield even more precise measurements of the Δm²₂₃ and θ₂₃ parameters. These efforts will also extend our understanding of [neutrino](/Neutrino) interactions through enhanced [cross-section](/Cross_section_(physics)) measurements, thereby improving the theoretical models that underpin [neutrino](/Neutrino) generators. Crucially, these upgrades aim to further constrain the δCP phase, striving for a definitive confirmation of [CP symmetry](/CP_violation) violation in [neutrino oscillation](/Neutrino_oscillation) at a 3σ significance level during the [T2K-II](/T2K) phase, and an even more robust 5σ in the subsequent [Hyper-Kamiokande](/Hyper-Kamiokande) experiment. Because, apparently, 3σ isn't quite enough to satisfy the cosmic inquisitors.

## Neutrino beam

The entire enterprise hinges on a rather impressive feat of engineering: generating a precise [muon neutrino](/Muon_neutrino) or [muon antineutrino](/Muon_neutrino) [beam](/Accelerator_neutrino) at the [J-PARC](/J-PARC) facility. This process begins with a [proton beam](/Proton), which is gradually coerced into higher energies by a sophisticated system of three [particle accelerators](/Particle_accelerator). First, the [protons](/Proton) are accelerated to a modest 400 [MeV](/Megaelectronvolt) by the Linac linear accelerator. They then receive a significant boost, reaching 3 [GeV](/Gigaelectronvolt) in the RCS (Rapid Cycle Synchrotron), before finally being pushed to a formidable 30 [GeV](/Gigaelectronvolt) by the MR [synchrotron](/Synchrotron) (Main Ring).

These highly energetic [protons](/Proton) are then directed to collide with a [graphite](/Graphite) target, a collision that produces a veritable shower of [mesons](/Meson), predominantly [pions](/Pion) and [kaons](/Kaon). These secondary particles are then meticulously focused by a set of three [magnetic horns](/Magnetic_horn) and guided into a specialized tunnel known as the decay volume. The polarity of these [horns](/Magnetic_horn) is critical; by adjusting it, either positive or negative particles can be focused. Positive [pions](/Pion) and [kaons](/Kaon) predominantly decay into μ⁺ and νᵤ, thus forming a [muon neutrino](/Muon_neutrino) [beam](/Particle_beam). Conversely, negative [pions](/Pion) and [kaons](/Kaon) decay primarily into μ⁻ and νᵤ, creating a [muon antineutrino](/Muon_neutrino) [beam](/Particle_beam). Any remaining [hadrons](/Hadron) and charged [leptons](/Lepton) are summarily stopped by a robust 75-ton [graphite](/Graphite) block, the "beam dump," and further attenuated by the surrounding ground. The [neutrinos](/Neutrino), however, being the elusive ghosts they are, sail unimpeded through the Earth, continuing their journey towards the far detector. It's a surprisingly violent process for creating something so insubstantial.

### Off-axis beam

[T2K](/T2K) prides itself on being the pioneering experiment to implement the concept of an off-axis [neutrino beam](/Accelerator_neutrino). The [neutrino beam](/Neutrino_beam) at [J-PARC](/J-PARC) is intentionally configured to deviate by 2 to 3 [degrees](/Degree_(angle)) from the direct line-of-sight to the [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) far detector, and similarly from one of the near detectors, ND280. This seemingly odd choice is, in fact, a stroke of deliberate genius. The average energy of the [neutrinos](/Neutrino) decreases proportionally with their deviation from the beam axis.

The specific off-axis angle of 2.5° was chosen with calculated precision to maximize the probability of [oscillation](/Neutrino_oscillation) at the specific distance of the far detector. For a baseline of 295 kilometers (183 mi), this maximal [oscillation](/Neutrino_oscillation) probability occurs for [neutrinos](/Neutrino) with an energy around 600 [MeV](/Megaelectronvolt). In this particular [neutrino](/Neutrino) energy range, the dominant interaction type is [charged current](/Charged_current) quasielastic interactions. Crucially, for these interactions, the energy of the incoming [neutrino](/Neutrino) can be reconstructed with remarkable accuracy solely based on the momentum and direction of the resulting charged [lepton](/Lepton). Furthermore, this off-axis configuration cleverly suppresses higher [neutrino](/Neutrino) energies, thereby reducing the number of interactions that produce [mesons](/Meson)—interactions that would otherwise act as unwanted background noise in the delicate oscillation analysis conducted by the [T2K](/T2K) experiment. It's a subtle manipulation, but one that significantly cleans up the signal.

## Near detectors

The complex of near detectors, a crucial component in this grand cosmic ballet, is strategically positioned a mere 280 meters (920 ft) from the [graphite](/Graphite) target. Its primary directive, if one were to distill it, is to meticulously measure the [neutrino flux](/Neutrino_flux) *before* any significant [oscillations](/Neutrino_oscillation) can occur, and to diligently study the intricate details of [neutrino](/Neutrino) interactions. This system is a tripartite marvel, consisting of three main detectors, each with its own specialized role:

*   **[INGRID detector](/INGRID_detector)** (Interactive Neutrino GRID), which, as its name subtly hints, is situated directly on the axis of the [neutrino beam](/Neutrino_beam). It's the primary monitor, ensuring the beam is behaving as expected.
*   **[ND280 detector](/ND280_detector)**, which is positioned 2.5° away from the beam axis, mirroring the exact off-axis angle of the far detector. This is where the crucial pre-oscillation measurements that directly inform the far detector analysis are made.
*   **[WAGASCI-BabyMIND](/WAGASCI-BabyMIND)** (WAter Grid SCIntillator Detector – prototype Magnetized Iron Neutrino Detector), a magnetized [neutrino](/Neutrino) detector situated at a 1.5° off-axis angle. Its purpose is to explore the subtle variations in the energy spectrum with different off-axis angles and to measure [cross-sections](/Cross_section_(physics)) at slightly higher average [neutrino](/Neutrino) energies. Because one angle is never enough, apparently.

### Signal readout

The operational principle behind the signal readout in the [T2K](/T2K) near detectors, with the notable exception of the [Time Projection Chambers](/Time_Projection_Chamber) (TPCs) within ND280, relies entirely on [plastic](/Plastic) [scintillator](/Scintillator) material. This scintillator, the active medium, is designed to emit light when traversed by charged particles. The light produced by these fleeting charged particles within the [plastic scintillator](/Plastic_scintillator) bars and planes is then efficiently collected by [wavelength-shifting](/Wavelength_shifter) [fibres](/Optical_fiber). These fibers, in turn, channel the light to highly sensitive Hamamatsu [Multi-pixel photon counters](/Silicon_photomultiplier), strategically placed at one or both ends of the fibers. The scintillator bars themselves are meticulously organized into layers. In a rather clever design, bars in two adjacent layers are oriented perpendicularly to each other, a configuration that collectively provides comprehensive 3D information about the trajectory of the traversing particles. It's a sophisticated system for capturing the brief, luminous trails of subatomic interactions.

### INGRID detector

The [INGRID detector](/INGRID_detector)'s primary mission is the routine monitoring of the [neutrino beam](/Neutrino_beam)'s direction and intensity. It does this on a daily basis, directly registering [neutrino](/Neutrino) interactions. One might say it's the beam's personal watchdog. The [INGRID detector](/INGRID_detector) itself is composed of 16 identical modules, arranged in a distinctive cross shape: 7 modules forming a vertical arm and 7 forming a horizontal arm, with an additional 2 modules positioned outside the main cross. The sheer scale of these arms, stretching 10 meters (33 ft) in both height and width, is a testament to the meticulousness required for such measurements.

Each individual module is constructed from alternating layers of [iron](/Iron) and [plastic scintillator](/Plastic_scintillator). To further refine its detection capabilities, an additional 4 [veto](/Veto_detector) layers of scintillator encircle each module. These [veto](/Veto_detector) layers are crucial for distinguishing between particles originating from interactions within the module itself and those merely entering from the outside, thereby reducing background noise. The vast majority of a single module's mass—a substantial 7.1 tons—is comprised of [iron](/Iron), accounting for 96% of its total weight. Positioned precisely on the [neutrino beam](/Neutrino_beam) axis, at the very heart of the cross between the vertical and horizontal arms, resides an additional module: the Proton Module. This particular module, weighing 0.55 tons, is constructed solely from layers of [plastic scintillator](/Plastic_scintillator). Its specific purpose is to record quasielastic interactions and to compare these observed events with theoretical simulations, ensuring the models align with reality.

### ND280 detector

The [ND280 detector](/ND280_detector) is not merely a detector; it's a sophisticated instrument designed to provide a comprehensive snapshot of the [neutrino flux](/Neutrino_flux), its energy spectrum, and the unwelcome presence of [electron neutrino](/Electron_neutrino) beam pollution—all measured at the precise off-axis angle utilized by the far detector. Beyond these essential flux measurements, [ND280](/ND280_detector) also meticulously investigates various types of [muon](/Muon) and [electron neutrino](/Electron_neutrino) and antineutrino interactions. The sum of these efforts allows physicists to accurately estimate the expected number and specific types of interactions that will occur in the distant far detector. This, in turn, significantly reduces the systematic error inherent in [neutrino oscillation](/Neutrino_oscillation) analyses, particularly those stemming from models of [neutrino](/Neutrino) interactions and flux. It's a necessary evil, this constant calibration.

The [ND280](/ND280_detector) system is a composite marvel, housing a suite of inner sub-detectors: the Pi-Zero detector and a tracker assembly comprising two Fine-Grained Detectors (FGDs) intricately interleaved with three [Time Projection Chambers](/Time_Projection_Chamber) (TPCs). This entire delicate inner structure is encased within a metal frame, affectionately termed a "basket." Surrounding this basket are the layers of the electromagnetic calorimeter, all nestled within a recycled magnet from the venerable [UA1 experiment](/UA1_experiment). This magnet generates a uniform, horizontal [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field) of 0.2 [Tesla](/Tesla_(unit)), and its instrumented scintillator planes form the Side Muon Range Detector. It's a Frankenstein's monster of detectors, but a highly effective one.

#### Pi-Zero detector

The Pi-Zero (π⁰) Detector (P0D) is a rather cunning device, consisting of 40 planes of [plastic scintillator](/Plastic_scintillator) modules. In its central region, these planes are interleaved with 2.8 cm thick bags, which can be filled with [water](/Water), and substantial brass sheets. In contrast, the two peripheral regions feature scintillator modules sandwiched with lead sheets. The genius of this design lies in its ability to directly measure [neutrino](/Neutrino) interactions on [water](/Water)—the target material within the [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) far detector. This is achieved by comparing the interaction rates between modes when the bags are filled with water and when they are empty.

The active volume of the entire P0D is approximately 2.1 m × 2.2 m × 2.4 m (X×Y×Z), and its mass varies depending on whether the water bags are full or empty, ranging from 15.8 tons with water to 12.9 tons without.

The central objective of the Pi-Zero Detector is to precisely measure the production of neutral [pions](/Pion) in [neutral current](/Neutral_current) [neutrino](/Neutrino) interactions on [water](/Water), a process described as:

νᵤ + N → νᵤ + N' + π⁰

This reaction is particularly problematic because photons resulting from the π⁰ decay can be misidentified as an [electron](/Electron) within the [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) detector. Consequently, this process can mimic genuine [electron neutrino](/Electron_neutrino) interactions, constituting a significant and unwelcome background in the critical [electron neutrino](/Electron_neutrino) appearance measurement. The P0D, therefore, acts as a crucial sentinel against this deceptive mimicry.

#### Time projection chambers

The three [Time Projection Chambers](/Time_projection_chamber) (TPCs) are essentially gas-tight rectangular boxes, each a marvel of precision engineering. Within each TPC, a cathode plane is meticulously positioned at the center, flanked on both sides by readout [MicroMegas](/MicroMegas_detector) modules, arranged parallel to the cathode. These chambers are filled with an [argon](/Argon)-based drift gas, maintained at atmospheric pressure.

When a charged particle, with its inherent disregard for boundaries, traverses a TPC, it inevitably [ionises](/Ionisation) the gas along its path, leaving a trail of freed electrons. These ionization electrons, under the influence of an electric field, then drift from the central cathode towards the sides of the TPC. There, they are detected by the [MicroMegas](/MicroMegas_detector) modules, which meticulously record their arrival positions. This provides a detailed 3D image of the charged particle's ephemeral journey. The Y and Z coordinates are directly derived from the position of the detected ionization electrons on the [MicroMegas](/MicroMegas_detector) modules, while the X coordinate is ingeniously determined by the drift time of these electrons.

Placed within a [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field), the curvature of the particle's reconstructed path allows for the precise determination of its [electric charge](/Electric_charge) and [momentum](/Momentum). Furthermore, the amount of ionization electrons generated per unit distance provides a crucial means of particle identification, a method underpinned by the venerable [Bethe-Bloch formula](/Bethe_formula). It's a complex dance of particles and fields, all orchestrated to reveal the invisible.

#### Fine-grained detectors

Two Fine-Grained Detectors (FGDs) are strategically positioned within the [ND280](/ND280_detector) detector, one after the first TPC and another after the second. Together, these FGDs and TPCs form the sophisticated tracker system of [ND280](/ND280_detector). The FGDs serve a dual purpose: they provide the active target mass for the [neutrino](/Neutrino) interactions themselves, and they are capable of precisely measuring the characteristically short tracks left by recoiling [protons](/Proton).

The first FGD is constructed entirely from layers of [scintillator](/Scintillator). In contrast, the second FGD employs an alternating layered structure of [scintillator](/Scintillator) and [water](/Water). This deliberate incorporation of [water](/Water) into the second FGD is critical, as the [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) far detector is, of course, entirely [water](/Water)-based. By comparing the [neutrino](/Neutrino) interactions observed in these two distinct FGDs, physicists can accurately determine the [cross-sections](/Cross_section_(physics)) for interactions occurring on [carbon](/Carbon) (from the scintillator) and on [water](/Water). It’s a clever way to isolate the crucial water-based interactions.

#### Electromagnetic Calorimeter

The Electromagnetic Calorimeter (ECal) forms a protective and analytical shell around the inner sub-detectors (P0D, TPCs, FGDs). It's a layered structure, meticulously constructed from [scintillator](/Scintillator) layers interleaved with lead absorber sheets. Its multifaceted role is to detect neutral particles, particularly photons, and to precisely measure their energy and direction. Additionally, it serves to detect charged particles, providing supplementary information vital for their accurate identification. In essence, it's the detector's comprehensive "eye" for energy and particle type, ensuring that little escapes its watchful gaze.

#### Side Muon Range Detector

The Side Muon Range Detector (SMRD) consists of specialized [scintillator](/Scintillator) modules, ingeniously inserted into the gaps within the main magnet structure of [ND280](/ND280_detector). Its primary function is to record [muons](/Muon) that manage to escape the inner confines of the detector, particularly those traveling at large angles relative to the beam direction. While most other particle types (barring [neutrinos](/Neutrino), naturally) are typically stopped within the calorimeter, the SMRD ensures that these escaping [muons](/Muon) are still accounted for. Beyond its role in tracking, the SMRD can also function as a [trigger](/Trigger_(particle_physics)) for incoming [cosmic rays](/Cosmic_rays), providing valuable calibration and background data. Finally, and rather crucially, it assists in identifying beam interactions that occur within the surrounding walls of the cavern or even within the magnet itself, ensuring a clean signal for the primary experiment.

### WAGASCI-BabyMIND

[WAGASCI-BabyMIND](/WAGASCI-BabyMIND) is the new kid on the block, strategically positioned adjacent to the established [INGRID](/INGRID_detector) and [ND280](/ND280_detector) detectors. This specialized detector is dedicated to refining our understanding of [neutrino](/Neutrino) interaction studies. It rather proudly delivered its first tranche of [neutrino beam](/Neutrino_beam) data, utilizing its full detector setup, during the 2019/2020 winter run. A successful debut, one might say.

The [WAGASCI-BabyMIND](/WAGASCI-BabyMIND) system is not a monolithic entity but rather an intricate assembly of several sub-detectors, each playing a vital role:

*   **Two new [water](/Water)-[scintillator](/Scintillator) detectors (WAGASCI, WAter-Grid-SCIntillator-Detector):** These serve as both the primary [water](/Water) targets for [neutrino](/Neutrino) interactions and as particle trackers. Their innovative 3D grid-like structure, formed by [scintillator](/Scintillator) bars, creates hollow cavities meticulously filled with [water](/Water). This design achieves a remarkable [water](/Water)-to-[scintillator](/Scintillator) mass ratio (80% H₂O + 20% CH) and ensures a high, remarkably uniform acceptance across all directions.
*   **One Proton Module:** Identical to its counterpart in the [INGRID detector](/INGRID_detector), this module is constructed from plain [plastic scintillator](/Plastic_scintillator) (CH) bars. It functions as the primary CH target and particle tracker, providing a crucial comparative baseline.
*   **Two WallMRD (Wall Muon Range Detector):** These are non-magnetized [muon](/Muon) spectrometers, designed to detect [muons](/Muon) traveling sideways. They are ingeniously constructed from passive [iron](/Iron) planes intertwined with active [scintillator](/Scintillator) planes, offering a robust means of tracking these escaping particles.
*   **One BabyMIND (prototype Magnetized Iron Neutrino Detector):** This is a magnetized [muon](/Muon) spectrometer, specifically designed to detect forward-going [muons](/Muon). BabyMIND boasts an original, sandwich-like configuration of [scintillation](/Scintillator) modules intertwined with magnetized [ferrite](/Ferrite_(iron)) modules. The modular nature of its design allows for easy rearrangement, adapting the [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field) to the specific requirements of the experiment. A key advantage is its power efficiency, as the [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field) is confined solely within the [ferrite](/Ferrite_(iron)), unlike magnets that must magnetize empty spaces, such as the [ND280](/ND280_detector) magnet. However, this design presents a persistent challenge: the [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field) is not homogeneous throughout the [muons](/Muon)' travel volume, complicating [momentum](/Momentum) reconstruction. A minor inconvenience in the grand scheme.

All active material within these detectors is composed of [plastic scintillator](/Plastic_scintillator), with signal readout performed precisely as detailed in the "Signal readout" section.

The overarching goal of the [WAGASCI-BabyMIND](/WAGASCI-BabyMIND) detector is to reduce the systematic error that plagues [T2K](/T2K)'s [oscillation](/Neutrino_oscillation) analysis. This will be achieved through its deliberate complementarity with the [ND280 detector](/ND280_detector):

*   The differing target materials between [ND280](/ND280_detector) (80% CH + 20% H₂O) and [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) (pure H₂O) necessitate reliance on complex [cross-section](/Cross_section_(physics)) models to disentangle the H₂O [cross-section](/Cross_section_(physics)) estimate from the CH one. The high fraction of [water](/Water) (80%) in the [WAGASCI](/WAGASCI-BabyMIND) [water-scintillator](/Water-scintillator) modules will enable a direct measurement of the [charged-current](/Charged_current) [neutrino](/Neutrino) [cross-section](/Cross_section_(physics)) ratio between [water](/Water) (H₂O) and [plastic](/Plastic) (CH) with an impressive 3% accuracy. A precision that, while seemingly small, can make a world of difference.
*   The new detector will provide highly precise measurements of various [charged-current](/Charged_current) [neutrino](/Neutrino) interaction channels, boasting a lower [momentum](/Momentum) threshold and full angular acceptance. These improvements will significantly constrain uncertainties in flux and [cross-section](/Cross_section_(physics)) models for particles produced at high angles. Such assets will also facilitate the detection of low-[momentum](/Momentum) [hadrons](/Hadron) produced in [neutrino](/Neutrino) interactions with bound states of two [nucleons](/Nucleon) or through reinteractions inside the target [nucleus](/Atomic_nucleus) of particles initially produced by the [neutrino](/Neutrino). This, in turn, promises a more accurate modeling of such interactions in the far detector.
*   Its location, at the same 280-meter distance from the [graphite](/Graphite) target as [ND280](/ND280_detector) and [INGRID](/INGRID_detector), but at a distinct off-axis angle of 1.5 [degrees](/Degree_(angle)), means that the energy spectrum of the [neutrino beam](/Neutrino_beam) peaks at different energies for each detector's off-axis angle. A [combination](/Linear_combination) of measurements from these disparate detectors will provide a vastly improved constraint on the [neutrino cross-sections](/Cross_section_(physics)) as a function of their energy. It's a multi-pronged attack on uncertainty.

## Super-Kamiokande

The [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) detector, a monumental structure, is buried 1000 meters underground within the Mozumi Mine, beneath Mount Ikeno in the [Kamioka](/Kamioka,_Gifu) area of [Hida](/Hida,_Gifu) city. It is, to put it mildly, a massive [stainless steel](/Stainless_steel) [cylindrical](/Cylinder) tank, approximately 40 meters in both height and diameter. This immense vessel is filled with a staggering 50,000 tons of ultra-pure [water](/Water) and painstakingly instrumented with around 13,000 [photomultiplier tubes](/Photomultiplier_tube) (PMTs).

Its operational principle is elegantly simple, yet profoundly effective: it detects a [cone](/Cone) of [Cherenkov light](/Cherenkov_radiation) emitted by charged particles that are moving through the [water](/Water) faster than light itself can in that medium. The detector's primary objective within [T2K](/T2K) is to measure [muons](/Muon) and [electrons](/Electron) produced in [charged current](/Charged_current) quasielastic interactions (CCQE) of νᵤ and νₑ, respectively.

Due to their relatively larger mass, [muons](/Muon) tend to maintain their trajectory, producing a sharply defined [cone](/Cone) of [Cherenkov light](/Cherenkov_radiation) that the PMTs register as a clear, distinct ring. [Electrons](/Electron), on the other hand, possessing a much smaller mass, are far more prone to scattering and almost invariably generate electromagnetic [showers](/Particle_shower). These showers manifest to the PMTs as rings with characteristically fuzzy edges. The energy of the interacting [neutrino](/Neutrino) is then meticulously calculated based on the direction and energy of the charged [lepton](/Lepton) produced in the CCQE interaction. Through this process, the νᵤ and νₑ spectra are precisely determined, leading to the measurement of the crucial [oscillation](/Neutrino_oscillation) parameters relevant for both [muon neutrino](/Muon_neutrino) disappearance and [electron neutrino](/Electron_neutrino) appearance. It's a rather intricate way to observe something that, to the naked eye, is entirely invisible.

## History

[T2K](/T2K) isn't an entirely new venture; it proudly stands as the successor to the [KEK](/KEK) to [Kamioka](/Kamioka,_Gifu) ([K2K](/K2K_experiment)) experiment, which, in its time, operated from 1999 to 2004. During the [K2K experiment](/K2K_experiment), an [accelerator beam](/Accelerator_neutrino) of [muon neutrinos](/Muon_neutrino) was generated at the [KEK](/KEK) facility in [Tsukuba](/Tsukuba,_Ibaraki), [Japan](/Japan), and dispatched towards the [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) detector, located a mere 250 km away. The results from [K2K](/K2K_experiment) were quite significant, confirming at an impressive confidence level of 99.9985% (4.3 [σ](/Standard_deviation)) the [disappearance](/Neutrino_oscillation) of [muon neutrinos](/Muon_neutrino). These findings were remarkably consistent with previous measurements of [oscillation](/Neutrino_oscillation) parameters obtained by the [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) detector for [atmospheric neutrinos](/Neutrino), providing a solid foundation for future research.

The construction of the [neutrino beamline](/Neutrino_beamline) for [T2K](/T2K) commenced in 2004, a process that, surprisingly, concluded with successful commissioning in 2009. The entire [INGRID detector](/INGRID_detector) and the majority of the [ND280 detector](/ND280_detector) (save for the barrel section of the electromagnetic calorimeter) were also completed in 2009. The final missing piece of the calorimeter puzzle was installed in the autumn of 2010. The far detector for [T2K](/T2K) is, of course, the venerable and massive [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) detector, which has been diligently operating since 1996, tirelessly studying [proton lifetime](/Proton_lifetime) and the [oscillations](/Neutrino_oscillation) of [atmospheric](/Neutrino), [solar](/Solar_neutrino), and [accelerator](/Accelerator_neutrino) [neutrinos](/Neutrino). It’s seen a lot, that detector.

The [T2K](/T2K) experiment officially began collecting [neutrino](/Neutrino) data for physics analysis in January 2010, initially with an incomplete [ND280 detector](/ND280_detector). By November 2010, the full setup was finally operational. However, this grand endeavor was abruptly interrupted for a full year by the devastating [Great Tohoku Earthquake](/Great_Tohoku_Earthquake) in March 2011, a stark reminder that even the most cutting-edge science is at the mercy of geological forces. Following this unforeseen hiatus, the [proton beam](/Proton_beam) power, and consequently the [neutrino beam](/Neutrino_beam) intensity, steadily increased. By February 2020, it had reached a formidable power of 515 [kW](/Kilowatt), accumulating a total of 3.6×10²¹ [protons](/Proton) on target. Data collection was split, with 55% in [neutrino-mode](/Neutrino_mode) and 45% in [antineutrino-mode](/Antineutrino_mode), ensuring a comprehensive study of both matter and antimatter counterparts.

## Future plans

The [T2K](/T2K) experiment, in its current configuration, operated until 2020. However, the pursuit of knowledge, much like the universe itself, never truly ceases. In 2021, a significant milestone was achieved: the first data run with [gadolinium](/Gadolinium) loaded into the [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) far detector. A bold step, as we shall see.

The period of 2021–2022 is slated for a major upgrade of both the [neutrino beamline](/Neutrino_beamline) and the [ND280](/ND280_detector) near detector. Following these enhancements, from 2023 until 2026, [neutrino](/Neutrino) data will be collected as part of the second phase of the [T2K](/T2K) experiment, aptly named [T2K-II](/T2K). Then, in 2027, the torch will be passed to the next generation: the [Hyper-Kamiokande](/Hyper-Kamiokande) (HK) experiment. This ambitious successor will feature a new, colossal 250,000-ton [water](/Water) [Cherenkov](/Cherenkov_radiation) far detector, the [Hyper-Kamiokande detector](/Hyper-Kamiokande), a truly monumental undertaking. Additionally, there's serious consideration for constructing an entirely new [intermediate detector](/Hyper-Kamiokande) at a distance of approximately 2 kilometers (1.2 mi) for the HK experiment. Because when it comes to detectors, apparently, bigger is always better, and more is always more.

### T2K-II

Phase II of the [T2K](/T2K) experiment is anticipated to commence at the beginning of 2023, with data taking having officially started in December 2023, and will continue its relentless pursuit of knowledge until 2026, just before the launch of the [Hyper-Kamiokande](/Hyper-Kamiokande) experiment. The physics goals for [T2K-II](/T2K) are nothing if not ambitious: a precise measurement of the [oscillation](/Neutrino_oscillation) parameters θ₂₃ and Δm²₂₃, aiming for an accuracy of 1.7° and 1%, respectively. Beyond mere precision, it seeks to unequivocally confirm, at a level of 3 [σ](/Standard_deviation) or greater, the existence of [matter-antimatter asymmetry](/CP_violation) in the [neutrino](/Neutrino) sector across a broad spectrum of possible true values for δCP—the parameter, as we've established, responsible for this very [CP](/CP_violation) (matter-antimatter) asymmetry.

Achieving these lofty goals demands a significant reduction in both statistical and systematic errors. To that end, a substantial upgrade of the beamline and the [ND280](/ND280_detector) detector is planned. Furthermore, a rather ingenious strategy involves doping the [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) [water](/Water) with [gadolinium](/Gadolinium), a move designed to enable ν/ν discrimination in the far detector. These hardware enhancements will be complemented by crucial improvements in software and analysis methodologies. It's an all-encompassing effort to squeeze every last drop of information from these elusive particles.

### Beam upgrade

The proposed beam upgrade plan for [T2K-II](/T2K-II) necessitates a year-long shutdown of the [J-PARC](/J-PARC) Main Ring [particle accelerator](/Particle_accelerator) in 2021. This temporary cessation of operations will be followed by a persistent, gradual increase in the [proton beam](/Proton_beam) power, continuing unabated until the commencement of the [Hyper-Kamiokande](/Hyper-Kamiokande) experiment. The expectation, or perhaps the demand, is that the beam power will reach 750 [kW](/Kilowatt) by 2022, and then further escalate to a formidable 1.3 [MW](/Megawatt) by 2029. Because more power, as they say, always means more data.

As of February 2020, the [proton beam](/Proton_beam) power had already achieved 515 [kW](/Kilowatt), delivering 2.7x10¹⁴ [protons](/Proton) per pulse with a repetition cycle of 2.48 seconds between pulses. To hit the 750 [kW](/Kilowatt) target, the repetition cycle will need to be slashed to 1.32 seconds, while maintaining 2.0x10¹⁴ [protons](/Proton) per pulse. For the truly ambitious 1.3 [MW](/Megawatt) goal, the repetition cycle must be further reduced to a blistering 1.16 seconds, and the number of [protons](/Proton) per pulse boosted to 3.2x10¹⁴. In addition to cranking up the primary [proton beam](/Proton_beam) power, the current in the [magnetic horns](/Magnetic_horn) that focus the secondary particles ([pions](/Pion), [kaons](/Kaon), and so forth) of a chosen [electric charge](/Electric_charge) will also be augmented, increasing from 250 [kA](/Kiloampere) to 320 [kA](/Kiloampere). This calculated increase is projected to boost the yield of "right-sign" [neutrinos](/Neutrino) (meaning [neutrinos](/Neutrino) in the [neutrino-mode](/Neutrino_mode) beam and [antineutrinos](/Antineutrino) in the [antineutrino-mode](/Antineutrino_mode) beam) by 10%. Conversely, it will reduce the contamination from "wrong-sign" [neutrinos](/Neutrino) ([antineutrinos](/Antineutrino) in the [neutrino-mode](/Neutrino_mode) beam and [neutrinos](/Neutrino) in the [antineutrino-mode](/Antineutrino_mode) beam) by a welcome 5–10%.

Achieving this relentless reduction in the repetition cycle will, predictably, necessitate a series of hardware upgrades. This includes a major overhaul of the Main Ring [power supplies](/Power_supply) and a more modest upgrade of the focusing [horn](/Magnetic_horn) [power supplies](/Power_supply), all of which are scheduled for installation during the extended shutdown in 2021. Increasing the [horn](/Magnetic_horn) current will demand the deployment of an additional (third) [horn](/Magnetic_horn) [power supply](/Power_supply). Simultaneously, the sheer increase in [proton beam](/Proton_beam) power mandates an enhancement of the [cooling](/Cooling) capacity for critical secondary beamline components, such as the [graphite](/Graphite) target, the [magnetic horns](/Magnetic_horn), and the beam dump. And, of course, the rather mundane but necessary task of managing a larger volume of irradiated [cooling](/Cooling) [water](/Water). It's a delicate balance of pushing limits and mitigating consequences.

### ND280 Upgrade

The current design of the [ND280 detector](/ND280_detector), while optimized for the detection and reconstruction of forward-going [leptons](/Lepton) ([muons](/Muon) and [electrons](/Electron)), also carries a rather inconvenient set of limitations. For instance, its reconstruction efficiency for particles produced almost perpendicular or even backward with respect to the interacting [neutrino](/Neutrino)'s direction is disappointingly low. Furthermore, its [momentum](/Momentum) threshold is simply too high to effectively reconstruct a significant portion of the produced [pions](/Pion) and the all-important knocked-out [nucleons](/Nucleon) ([protons](/Proton) and [neutrons](/Neutron)).

In [Charged Current Quasi-Elastic (CCQE) interactions](/Charged_current), which are the dominant interaction type in the [ND280](/ND280_detector) near detector, the kinematics of the produced [lepton](/Lepton) are generally sufficient for reconstructing the energy of the incoming [neutrino](/Neutrino). However, other types of [neutrino](/Neutrino) interactions where additional particles ([pions](/Pion), [kaons](/Kaon), [nucleons](/Nucleon)) are lost can be mistakenly reconstructed as CCQE events. This introduces a subtle but significant [bias](/Bias_(statistics)) into the reconstructed [neutrino](/Neutrino) energy spectrum. Therefore, it's not merely desirable but *essential* to optimize the detector to be acutely sensitive to these additional particles and the complex [nuclear effects](/Nuclear_structure) at play.

To address these critical issues, three primary measures must be implemented:

*   The detector must be capable of efficiently detecting [nucleons](/Nucleon) in the final state of [neutrino](/Neutrino) interactions. This necessitates a substantial lowering of the detection thresholds.
*   High-angle and backward-going tracks must be reconstructed with high fidelity. This is achieved by expanding the angular acceptance and significantly improving the efficiency of discriminating between backward and forward-going tracks using precise timing information.
*   Finally, the total fiducial volume—the active mass available for [neutrino](/Neutrino) interactions—within the tracker part of the [ND280 detector](/ND280_detector), characterized by its superior reconstruction capabilities, needs to be enlarged. This will, quite simply, increase the rate of observed [neutrino](/Neutrino) interactions.

The [ND280 Upgrade](/ND280_Upgrade) directly tackles these requirements by replacing a portion of the existing P0D sub-detector with three distinct types of novel sub-detectors. The downstream section, which currently houses two Fine-Grained scintillation Detectors (FGDs) and three [Time Projection Chambers](/Time_Projection_Chamber) (TPCs), will retain its sandwiched architecture and continue its role in detecting forward-going [leptons](/Lepton) and high-[momentum](/Momentum) [hadrons](/Hadron). The upstream section, presently occupied by the P0D sub-detector, will be supplanted by three innovative components: a [scintillating](/Scintillator) 3D target known as the Super Fine-Grained Detector (SuperFGD), two new TPCs positioned above and below the SuperFGD (the High-Angle TPCs or HATPCs), and a ring of six Time-of-Flight (TOF) detectors encircling this new structure. Each of these sub-detectors merits a brief, if weary, description below. The installation of these new sub-detectors into [ND280](/ND280_detector) is scheduled for 2022.

#### SuperFGD

The SuperFGD is a rather compact yet potent detector, measuring 2 by 2 by 0.5 meters (6 ft 7 in × 6 ft 7 in × 1 ft 8 in). It's composed of approximately 2 million individual 1 cm³ [scintillating](/Scintillator) [polystyrene](/Polystyrene) [cubes](/Cube). These cubes are intricately woven with a network of [optical fibres](/Optical_fiber), meticulously designed to capture the light emitted by particles produced during interactions within the target. Unlike the more conventional current FGDs, the SuperFGD boasts a three-fold projective 2D readout, effectively providing a quasi-3D readout. This clever configuration dramatically enhances the detection of short tracks, doing so almost uniformly across all directions. Its unique geometry, coupled with the precision of the TOF detectors and the HATPCs, grants the SuperFGD the capability to detect fast-[neutrons](/Neutron), a feature that could prove invaluable in the nuanced reconstruction of [antineutrino](/Antineutrino) energy. It’s a small package, but it promises significant insight.

#### HATPC

The High Angle [Time Projection Chambers](/Time_Projection_Chamber) (HATPCs) are designed to envelop the SuperFGD within the plane perpendicular to the incoming [neutrino beam](/Neutrino_beam). Their design philosophy largely mirrors that of the existing TPCs, both relying on the proven [MicroMegas](/MicroMegas_detector) modules technology for track reconstruction. The truly novel aspect of the HATPCs, beyond their expanded high-angle coverage, lies in their adoption of resistive [MicroMegas](/MicroMegas_detector) technology. This involves the application of a layer of [resistive](/Electrical_resistance_and_conductance) material, which significantly enhances the charge-sharing capabilities of the [MicroMegas](/MicroMegas_detector) modules. The benefit? A reduction in the number of readout channels while simultaneously maintaining a spatial resolution comparable to, or even exceeding, that of the current TPCs. It’s a subtle but effective refinement.

#### TOF

The six Time-of-Flight (TOF) detectors, positioned to encircle the HATPCs and SuperFGD, are comprised of a series of [plastic scintillator](/Plastic_scintillator) layers. Their design objective is to definitively identify the directional sense of a particle by precisely measuring the [time of flight](/Time_of_flight) for each crossing track, achieving an impressive timing resolution on the order of 140 [picoseconds](/Picosecond). The ability to discern the direction of a track has already proven to be critically important in the existing [ND280](/ND280_detector), where it plays a vital role in reducing background noise generated outside the active inner detectors. It's a fundamental piece of the puzzle, ensuring that what's observed is truly what's intended.

### Impact on Neutrino Oscillation Physics

The impending [ND280 Upgrade](/ND280_Upgrade) is poised to have a dual impact on the analyses conducted at [T2K](/T2K). Firstly, the sheer increase in statistics, courtesy of the 2-ton SuperFGD target, is expected to nearly double the amount of available data in specific samples. Quantity, as they say, has a quality all its own. Secondly, and arguably more profoundly, the new detector configuration will significantly enhance the detection capabilities for additional final state particles. This includes high-angle particles, thanks to the expanded angular acceptance, and less energetic particles, due to the lowered detection thresholds. This improvement in detector acceptance is crucial for covering almost the entire phase space accessible at the far detector ([Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande)).

Moreover, the ability to observe these final state particles will allow for a deeper probing of the complex [nuclear effects](/Nuclear_structure) that are absolutely essential for constraining the systematic uncertainties in [oscillation](/Neutrino_oscillation) analyses. This represents a significant stride towards transitioning from current inclusive models—which primarily rely on the final state [lepton](/Lepton) for predictions—to more nuanced semi-inclusive or exclusive models in [neutrino oscillation](/Neutrino_oscillation) physics. It’s a move towards a more complete, and hopefully less frustrating, understanding.

### SK-Gd

The third crucial element slated for improvement within [T2K](/T2K)'s Phase II is the introduction of [gadolinium](/Gadolinium) into the [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) detector, which, until recently, was filled solely with ultra-pure [water](/Water). A key limitation of [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) has been its inability to measure the [electric charge](/Electric_charge) of registered particles. This means it couldn't distinguish between a [neutrino](/Neutrino) and an [antineutrino](/Antineutrino) interaction based on the [charge](/Electric_charge) of the produced [lepton](/Lepton) (e.g., a μ⁻ is produced by a νᵤ, whereas a μ⁺ is produced by a νᵤ).

In (anti)[neutrino-nucleus interactions](/Neutrino-nucleus_interaction), beyond the production of a charged [lepton](/Lepton), a [nucleon](/Nucleon) is typically ejected from the [atomic nucleus](/Atomic_nucleus). Due to [charge conservation](/Charge_conservation), for [neutrinos](/Neutrino), this ejected particle is predominantly a [proton](/Proton), while for [antineutrinos](/Antineutrino), it's typically a [neutron](/Neutron):

νl + n → ℓ⁻ + p
νl + p → ℓ⁺ + n

The [Cherenkov energy threshold](/Cherenkov_radiation)—the minimum total energy a charged particle needs to produce [Cherenkov light](/Cherenkov_radiation)—is proportional to the particle's mass. In [water](/Water), this threshold is 0.8 [MeV](/Megaelectronvolt) for [electrons](/Electron), 160 [MeV](/Megaelectronvolt) for [muons](/Muon), and a substantial 1400 [MeV](/Megaelectronvolt) for [protons](/Proton). Consequently, [protons](/Proton) released in [neutrino](/Neutrino) interactions often fall below this threshold and remain undetected. [Neutrons](/Neutron), being neutral particles, inherently produce no [Cherenkov light](/Cherenkov_radiation). However, a [neutron](/Neutron) can be [absorbed](/Neutron_capture) by another [nucleus](/Atomic_nucleus), which then enters an [excited state](/Excited_state). During its subsequent deexcitation, this [nucleus](/Atomic_nucleus) emits [gamma rays](/Gamma_ray). These high-energy photons (for [gadolinium](/Gadolinium), their total energy is approximately 8 [MeV](/Megaelectronvolt)) can then [scatter electrons](/Compton_scattering) from atoms and/or [produce electron-positron pairs](/Pair_production), both of which *do* generate [Cherenkov light](/Cherenkov_radiation).

[Gadolinium](/Gadolinium) is a naturally occurring element that boasts the highest [cross-section](/Cross_section_(physics)) for capturing [neutrons](/Neutron) at [thermal](/Thermal_neutrons) energy. For 25 [meV](/Millielectronvolt) [neutrons](/Neutron), the [cross-section](/Cross_section_(physics)) for [gadolinium](/Gadolinium) is about 10⁵ times higher than for [hydrogen](/Hydrogen). The fraction of [neutrons](/Neutron) that will be captured in [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) is 50% for a 0.01% [gadolinium](/Gadolinium) concentration and a remarkable 90% for a 0.1% concentration—the planned final [gadolinium](/Gadolinium) concentration in [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande). The signal from [neutron capture](/Neutron_capture) is subtly delayed by a fraction of a [millisecond](/Millisecond) (accounting for the [neutron](/Neutron)'s travel time through the [water](/Water) before capture, plus the time [gadolinium](/Gadolinium) remains in its [excited state](/Excited_state)) relative to the charged [lepton](/Lepton) signal. This delayed signal typically appears within a distance of 50 cm (the average distance the [neutron](/Neutron) travels before capture) from the original [neutrino](/Neutrino) interaction point. Such a "double flash" event—the initial flash from the charged [lepton](/Lepton), followed by a second flash from the [gadolinium](/Gadolinium) deexcitation photons—serves as a clear signature of an [antineutrino](/Antineutrino) interaction. It's a rather elegant solution to a tricky problem.

The initial loading of 13 tons of Gd₂(SO₄)₃·8H₂O ([gadolinium(III) sulfate octahydrate](/Hydrate)) into the [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) [water](/Water) was meticulously carried out in July–August 2020, resulting in a 0.011% concentration of [gadolinium](/Gadolinium). [T2K](/T2K) then collected its first data with [gadolinium](/Gadolinium) in [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) in March–April 2021. The utilization of [gadolinium](/Gadolinium)-doped [water](/Water) will unlock new avenues of research, including the study of [remote supernova neutrinos](/Diffuse_supernova_neutrino_background), for which νₑ's are the most reactive in [Super-Kamiokande](/Super-Kamiokande) but were previously indistinguishable from [neutrinos](/Neutrino) originating from other sources. It will also significantly enhance the detector's performance for [supernova](/Supernova) explosions within [our galaxy](/Milky_Way) and allow for a more precise investigation of matter-antimatter differences in [accelerator neutrino](/Accelerator_neutrino) [oscillations](/Neutrino_oscillation). Because even the cosmos, it seems, has its secrets laid bare by meticulous chemical doping.

## Hyper-Kamiokande experiment

The designated successor to the [T2K](/T2K) experiment, the [Hyper-Kamiokande](/Hyper-Kamiokande) (HK) experiment, will leverage the upgraded accelerator system and [neutrino beamline](/Neutrino_beamline) currently in use, along with an enhanced suite of near detectors. However, this next-generation endeavor will also necessitate the construction of an entirely new far detector, the [Hyper-Kamiokande detector](/Hyper-Kamiokande), and potentially, an additional [intermediate detector](/Hyper-Kamiokande). As noted, a portion of the beam-related upgrade work and the improvements to the [ND280 detector](/ND280_detector) are being meticulously executed even before the official commencement of Phase II of the [T2K](/T2K) experiment. The [Hyper-Kamiokande](/Hyper-Kamiokande) experiment is projected to begin its operational phase around the year 2027. A date that, for some, is still a lifetime away, but for the universe, barely a blink.

